	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-mollycdesjardin odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-21388">
		<article id="comment-21388" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='https://2.gravatar.com/avatar/83b49bc6c01921ad52fd9aba3826fc1d?s=68&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=R' class='avatar avatar-68' height='68' width='68' /><span class="fn"><a href='http://www.mollydesjardin.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Molly Des Jardin</a></span> on <a href="https://tedunderwood.com/2015/06/04/seven-ways-humanists-are-using-computers-to-understand-text/#comment-21388"><time datetime="2015-06-09T08:43:50+00:00">June 9, 2015 at 8:43 am</time></a> <span class="says">said:</span>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>I really enjoyed this Ted, and the bibliography is so helpful. I do have an issue with the definition of unsupervised text analysis though; it simply means there is no training set, not that there&#8217;s no research question. I myself have employed unsupervised machine learning with specific research questions in mind in projects where I simply didn&#8217;t have the resources to create a training set, and took that into account when forming the research questions. I don&#8217;t think exploratory and having a research question are mutually exclusive. But anyway, this is a great post and thank you for it!</p>
</div>

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->

	<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-tedunderwood bypostauthor even depth-2 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-21389">
		<article id="comment-21389" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='https://1.gravatar.com/avatar/76dd28669b8c966858940eeb24cc684a?s=39&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=R' class='avatar avatar-39' height='39' width='39' /><span class="fn"><a href='https://tedunderwood.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>tedunderwood</a></span> on <a href="https://tedunderwood.com/2015/06/04/seven-ways-humanists-are-using-computers-to-understand-text/#comment-21389"><time datetime="2015-06-09T09:27:06+00:00">June 9, 2015 at 9:27 am</time></a> <span class="says">said:</span>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>You&#8217;re quite right about that. There are lots of clever ways to use topic modeling to get leverage on specific issues. If I remember rightly, Mohr and Bogdanov recommend being explicit about research goals in  <a href="http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304422X13000685" rel="nofollow">their intro to that <em>Poetics</em> issue on topic modeling,</a> and Andrew Goldstone and I definitely began our topic modeling work with some explicit hypotheses.</p>
<p>So I don&#8217;t mean to diss topic modeling as necessarily aimless, just noting that its popularity may have something to do with the fact that &#8220;you don&#8217;t <em>have</em> to start with a specific research question&#8221; (italics added). But that&#8217;s a slippery point, and one that needed clarification &#8212; thanks!</p>
</div>

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->

	<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-mollycdesjardin odd alt depth-3 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-21390">
		<article id="comment-21390" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='https://2.gravatar.com/avatar/83b49bc6c01921ad52fd9aba3826fc1d?s=39&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=R' class='avatar avatar-39' height='39' width='39' /><span class="fn"><a href='http://www.mollydesjardin.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Molly Des Jardin</a></span> on <a href="https://tedunderwood.com/2015/06/04/seven-ways-humanists-are-using-computers-to-understand-text/#comment-21390"><time datetime="2015-06-09T09:34:42+00:00">June 9, 2015 at 9:34 am</time></a> <span class="says">said:</span>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>Good point and I&#8217;m glad you made it clear in the post, by the way, since topic modeling is so popular and I feel like sometimes people treat it as an end in itself, especially if they&#8217;re new to computational methods in literary studies. Anyway, the unsupervised methods I used were not topic modeling (they were based in analysis of POS/grammatical patterns), so that&#8217;s why the description of unsupervised methods jumped out at me.</p>
<p>Regards-</p>
</div>

